'I've had a lot of fun with it,' she told the Today show. 'Everybody looks at it as such a sad thing, but it's really not, it's my new beginning... I feel better than I have in 18 months.'

She will now beginning physical therapy and will eventually be fitted for a prosthetic. 

Her husband Pete, who was at the marathon with DiMartino and her seven-year-old son Noah, said that he has no doubt that his wife with master the new limb.

'She is very stubborn, which is not really a bad thing because she will be told she can't do something and she just tries to do it anyway,' he told KHOU.

She told the channel she is also determine to recover so that the brothers who inflicted horror and pain on the city of Boston last year do not win.   

